I myself have a rug woven by my late mother, “Muisto Karjalasta”. By Norma Heimola. It was made in the 1970s. And she had this situation in the 1950s, after being evacuated, that with the wives of her uncles, they used this kind of material, dismantled felt from a paper machine. The felt from the paper machine was dismantled into yarn and dyed with dyes from plants. So this rug I now have in my archives, I’m wondering where should one put it. It dates from 1952, 1953. And its model is “Itämaan tietäjät”, or something like that, you can find it in the rug catalogs. And how skilfully these women have made decorations and embellishments for themselves, then after the war.
An old lady that I know, she turns 88 years on her next birthday, so she just moved into an assisted living building. And she would still like to make a rug for her granddaughter. She has made rugs for all her children and grandchildren during her lifetime.
It’s interesting, that as there are these ready-made packages, that artists and craft enthusiasts have produced and brought to market for us, so there is always extra yarn left from those packages. And then the people who are good at making crafts, they create new rugs from this extra yarn, rugs of their own design. And I've seen a few of the ones this lady has made. So it’s amazing how the creativity and skill increase. And one is not forced to make it according to the model.

Well then, another thing we thought of, started to think of, was that, it says here everywhere, that is this, this is a jerrycan. And Eero Rislakki has designed this, so VR can’t mean that either, his initials, but well, in any case this is a picture that brings me warm associations and the colour of the red can is lovely too, and well, that’s why I wanted to talk about this one.
And I chose this can when we had to choose one that we like from those pictures, and I chose this because the can gives me three associations, warm and beautiful associations. And then, the second thing that comes to mind, even though it’s not the same, is a canister I have at the cottage, which I use when going to pick blueberries. Now I sit on it when I pick blueberries, or I’m on my knees on it or somehow so that my back won’t hurt. So I was standing there thinking, and then the old lady in the shop came to me. And she didn’t try to sell me the sheep or anything, she just wanted to have a conversation with me. She asked me where I was from, why I was in Tallinn with my friends, and we just had a very spontantenous conversation.
This object reminds me of my trip to Tallinn with my friends and younger sister in 2017. We went on an overnight ferry from Helsinki to Tallinn. And that’s why we had a lot of time to have fun in (?). And the next thing I know is that I was really drunk on the ship. So, when we arrived in Tallinn I was tired and (?) because of the alcohol. But, since we were together, we decided to make the most of our trip, and enjoy the moment. So we roamed around Tallinn Old Town.
In the end, I decided to get myself the sheep, anyway, because I really felt like I had a good time in the shop and I wanted something to remind myself of it. So, I picked a black sheep from the whole collection and then I (?) to her that, “I picked this one because sometimes I think of myself as the black sheep of my family”. And she once again surprised me by her wise words. She told me: “Being a black sheep doesn’t mean that you are bad, it just means that you are unique”.
Then, this small arts and crafts shop caught my attention. So, I walked inside, and I was immediately drawn to this sheep object. It was something I had never seen before. And I really wanted to buy it, but I felt a bit (?) because I drank so much last night and caused my friends inconveniences.
And so the old lady left a huge impression on me. And now I realize I didn’t need the sheep to remind me of the shop, the old shop keeper and the whole experience, because I really enjoyed our spontantenous conversation. And I really hope that, by some miracle, I would be able to meet the old lady again, and tell her how much I cherished our conversation that day.

344521.pvalue:
I myself personally admired it at the home of my aunt, who was working on design herself, it was very early on, and, and to me, it represented a set of values that I already appreciated, already in my early teens. 
I believe that with today's technologies, it is possible to develop these products to products that are suitable to the time and durable, and I hope they will be seen in the future as well. The new generation will then gain from them the foundation, which is so splendidly available from them.
Eero Aarnio's chair Pastille represents to me one of the top products in Finnish design and these successful objects of the 1960s. Looking from today, from this angle, it is a bit of a controversial era and product, when plastic made its breakthrough in various products and designs. There was not so much concern for responsibility, and there was no talk of ecological material or such, but one went firmly forward and plastic represented modernism and, and a material which was very suitable for production in many ways. And even before, before the energy crises and so on.
And Pastille is also one of the most internationally successful products, our design products, and it’s always a pleasure to see it in different contexts and now even re-introduced in different places.

And at some point I got it in my head that I wanted a moped too. And I took part in a competition where the main price was a moped. But I didn't get that moped. And then, as time passed, the shared moped rides ended too, on summer vacation trips, but the moped stuck in my mind.
And this is a fun moped in that way, that it has the colours of the Finnish flag. And anyway, it was nice to be on a ride on it. And it always evokes feelings, when I see this.
I have this kind of Solifer moped here. I saw this picture over there, and it immediately brought to my mind the 1960s when I was young, in the late 1960s, early 1970s. So when we went to the cottage in Central Finland, there was, of course, one local boy who had such a moped, and of course I always wanted him to give me a ride, to try it. And it was so, of course, that I was a summer resident, and then he was, of course, a local. So then the next summer, if all went well, I got to ride on the same moped. And one time I did try to ride that moped myself too, but that didn't work out.
